<div class="container">
    <h1>HTTP Part 1</h1>
    <p><strong>HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)</strong> is the protocol used by browsers (clients) to communicate with web servers. It defines how requests are sent and how responses are received.</p>

    <h2>Main Concepts</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Request:</strong> The client sends an HTTP request to the server, specifying the method (GET, POST, etc.) and the resource.</li>
        <li><strong>Response:</strong> The server processes the request and sends back a response containing the requested data, usually with a status code.</li>
        <li>
            <strong>Methods:</strong> Common HTTP methods include:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>GET:</strong> Retrieve data from the server.</li>
                <li><strong>POST:</strong> Send data to the server.</li>
                <li><strong>PUT:</strong> Update existing data.</li>
                <li><strong>DELETE:</strong> Remove data.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Status Codes:</strong> Indicate the result of a request, e.g., <code>200 OK</code>, <code>404 Not Found</code>, <code>500 Internal Server Error</code>.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: HTTP GET Request</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-http">
GET /index.html HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0
Accept: text/html
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>This example shows a client requesting the <code>index.html</code> page from a server. The server will respond with the HTML content of that page.</p>

